CS:GO is a game that will grip you tightly and never let go. With its intense gameplay, immersive environments, and tactical challenges, it's easy to get sucked into the world of competitive online shooting.

But beware, for every hour you spend playing this game, it will take a little piece of your soul. Every match won or lost, every headshot landed or missed, every grenade thrown or dodged - they all add up, chipping away at your very being until you're left with nothing but a shell of your former self.

And yet, despite the toll it takes on you, you can't help but keep coming back for more. The rush of adrenaline as you defuse the bomb in the nick of time, the thrill of victory as you clutch the round for your team - these are the moments that make it all worth it.

In the end, CS:GO is not just a game, but a way of life. It will consume you, body and soul, until there is nothing left but the burning desire to play just one more match. So enter at your own risk, for once you start playing, there's no turning back.

If you're looking for a review on this game you've come to the wrong place, but if you're looking for an outstanding pie recipe you've come to the right place.

Ingredients:

1. 6 tablespoons unsalted butter
2. 1/2 cup white sugar
3. 1/2 cup brown sugar
4. 1/4 cup water
5. 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
6. 1 pinch salt
7. 5 apples - peeled, cored and sliced
8. 1 pastry for double-crust pie

Directions:

1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees F (220 degrees C).
2. Combine butter, white sugar, brown sugar, water, cinnamon, and salt in a saucepan over medium heat. Bring to a boil, remove from heat and set aside.
3. Roll out half the pastry to fit a 9-inch pie plate. Place bottom crust in pie plate; pour in apple slices.
4. Roll out top crust into a 10-inch circle. Cut into 8 (1-inch) wide strips with a sharp paring knife or pastry wheel. Weave the pastry strips, one at a time, into a lattice pattern. Fold the ends of the lattice strips under the edge of the bottom crust and crimp to seal.
5. Pour butter-sugar mixture over top of pie, coating the lattice, and allowing any remaining sauce to drizzle through the crust.
6. Bake in the preheated oven for 15 minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees F (175 degrees C), and bake until the crust is golden brown, the caramel on the top crust is set, and the apple filling is bubbling, 35 to 40 more minutes. Allow to cool completely before slicing.

Position 2 racks in the center of the oven, and preheat to 375 degrees F. Line 2 baking sheets with parchment.
Whisk together the flour, baking soda and 1 teaspoon salt in a large bowl.
Beat the butter and both sugars on medium-high speed in the bowl of a stand mixer fitted with a paddle attachment (or in a large bowl if using a handheld mixer) until light and fluffy, about 4 minutes. Add the eggs, one at time, beating after each addition to incorporate. Beat in the vanilla. Scrape down the side of the bowl as needed. Reduce the speed to medium, add the flour mixture and beat until just incorporated. Stir in the chocolate chips.
Scoop 12 heaping tablespoons of dough about 2 inches apart onto each prepared baking sheet. Roll the dough into balls with slightly wet hands. Bake, rotating the cookie sheets from upper to lower racks halfway through, until golden but still soft in the center, 12 to 15 minutes (the longer the cook time, the crunchier the cookies). Let cool for a few minutes on the baking sheet, and then transfer to a rack to cool completely.
Let the baking sheets cool completely, scoop the remaining dough onto 1 sheet and bake. Store the cookies in a tightly sealed container at room temperature for up to 5 days.


2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour

1 teaspoon baking soda

Fine salt

1 1/2 sticks (12 tablespoons) unsalted butter, at room temperature

3/4 cup packed light brown sugar

2/3 cup granulated sugar

2 large eggs

1 teaspoon pure vanilla extract

One 12-ounce bag semisweet chocolate chips

In conclusion, Counter-Strike: Global Offensive is a highly enjoyable and addictive first-person shooter with a dedicated fan base and a lot to offer. Piri-piri chicken with smashed sweet potatoes & broccoli:

Ingredients
3 large sweet potatoes (about 900g), peeled and cut into large chunks
oil, for drizzling
6-8 chicken thighs, skin left on
2 red onions, cut into wedges
25g sachet piri-piri spice mix (or a mild version, if you like)
300g long-stem broccoli

STEP 1
Heat the oven to 180C/160C fan/gas 4. Toss the sweet potatoes with a generous drizzle of oil and some seasoning, and tip into a very large roasting tin. Push the potatoes to one end of the tin, then, in the other end, toss the chicken with the onions, spice mix, a drizzle of oil and some seasoning. Roast for 40 mins, stirring everything halfway through. Add the broccoli to the tin, drizzle with a little oil and season, then roast for 10-15 mins more.

STEP 2
Remove the chicken, onions and broccoli from the tin. Roughly mash the potatoes using a fork, making sure you incorporate all the chicken juices and spices from the pan. Spread the mash over the base of the tin, then top with the broccoli, chicken and onions and serve from the tin in the middle of the table.

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CSGO) is a classic and highly acclaimed multiplayer first-person shooter that continues to reign supreme in the genre. While Valorant is a newer and worthy competitor, CSGO has a few advantages that make it a better game for many players.

One of CSGO's strengths is its emphasis on realism. The game's physics and movement mechanics are more grounded, providing a more immersive and authentic experience. This also means that gunplay is more realistic, with weapons having more recoil and requiring greater skill to use effectively.

In addition, CSGO's maps are more intricate and better designed, providing more opportunities for strategic play. The game's long-standing competitive scene has also cultivated a vibrant and passionate community, with an abundance of resources available for players to improve their skills.

Another advantage of CSGO over Valorant is its accessibility. CSGO is available on all major gaming platforms, including PC, Xbox, and PlayStation, whereas Valorant is currently only available on PC.

Finally, CSGO's frequent updates and new content releases keep the game fresh and exciting, while Valorant has yet to establish a similar track record of consistent updates.

In conclusion, while both CSGO and Valorant are excellent first-person shooters, CSGO has a few advantages that make it a better game for many players. Its focus on realism, intricate map design, accessibility, and consistent updates make it a must-play for anyone who loves competitive FPS games.

The standard game mode (Bomb Scenario) involves either defending or exploiting a bomb site. I spent most of my test-play time playing this mode, but I did branch out to the Arms Race and Hostage modes. Most competitive matches that I've watched stick with the Bomb Scenario match type, as well, which is another reason for the mode's popularity.

The Bomb Scenario mode comprises a maximum of 15 elimination-style rounds that last until one side wins a majority of the rounds. Players spawn either on the Terrorist (T) or Counter-Terrorists (CT) side, which determines the objective. Terrorists need to plant a bomb at one of the two marked bomb sites on the map. The CT team must prevent the terrorists from planting the bomb or defuse it before it explodes (the bomb has a countdown timer of 40 seconds). The defuse process itself takes 5 seconds, so getting to the bomb site quickly is a priority. Of course, eliminating all the players on the other side makes this objective easier, so keep an eye out for enemies at all times.

CS: GO's Bomb Scenario mode is a simple, yet enjoyable, twist on the standard multiplayer FPS setup, which opens up a ton of variability in each round. Another game mode, called Hostage, flips the tables and has the Terrorists defend a hostage, while the Counter-Terrorists attempt a rescue mission. CS: GO typically gets new mission-based modes with new operations. The current operation, Operation Hydra (released in May 2017) brought War Games, Wingman, and Weapons Expert modes to the game. These modes introduce twists on regular gameplay and affect the available weapons, the match objective, and the playable maps. These operations typically include a narrative-driven campaign, too.

This game has ever since brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside the house together as well. Back in 2015 my friend suggested to me the purchase of this game, i have played CS 1.6 previously so I thought it's time for an upgrade, i took my mums credit card and purchased the game, little did i know it was a beginning to something new, just after 2 weeks of playing, i started to feel, act and think differently, nothing was the same anymore, me and my friends played the game every day, mainly competitive, after a couple months i noticed a big change in my life... i stopped leaving the house and the only thing on my mind was how can i build up the ELO in CSGO, but was it my rank that i really cared about or was it something different... one day after a great game of CSGO i decided to go beat my meat, so i launch my browser and look for some spicy videos, little did i know that was the day I realised what the game has in fact done to me, instead of enjoying watching young Sasha Grey's box getting pounded, instead i started focusing on the male actor, admiring his large piece for the entirety of the video, at first i thought it was jealousy as i dont own a large rod myself, but after a while of rubbing my salami stick i've realised it's deeper than that, i realised i was gay. I never felt this way about another man's tool until i have had the taste of Counter Strike Global Offensive, i believe it was the source of my conversion, now after over 1000 hours in the game i have met another player from Estonia with a similar experience. Now we are married happily with 2 amazing kids, i believe this would have never happened if it wasnt for CSGO, so i'd like to thank valve, and all the developers involed, because if it wasnt for you i'd most likely would still be living a sad straight life. Definitely recommend 10/10

As someone who has been playing Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) for over a decade now, I can confidently say that this game has become an integral part of my life. With its intense gameplay, strategic depth, and endless replayability, CS:GO has remained one of the most engaging and exciting competitive games in the world.

One of the things that I appreciate the most about CS:GO is its emphasis on teamwork and communication. In order to succeed in this game, players must work together to devise and execute effective strategies, communicate effectively, and rely on each other's strengths to overcome the enemy team. This not only creates a sense of camaraderie and teamwork, but also encourages players to develop important skills such as leadership, communication, and decision-making.

Another aspect of CS:GO that has kept me hooked for so long is its intricate and complex gameplay mechanics. From the various weapons and grenades to the different types of maps and game modes, CS:GO offers a wealth of different gameplay elements that require players to constantly adapt and evolve their playstyles. Whether it's learning how to master the recoil patterns of a particular gun, or memorizing the angles and timings of a certain map, there is always something new to discover and master in CS:GO.

Of course, no review of CS:GO would be complete without mentioning its vibrant and passionate community. From the dedicated competitive players to the creative content creators, the CS:GO community is filled with people who are truly passionate about the game and who have helped make it the iconic title that it is today. Whether it's watching professional matches or streaming your own gameplay, there is always something exciting and engaging happening within the CS:GO community.

In conclusion, after 10 years of playing CS:GO, I can confidently say that this game is not just a game, but a way of life. Its intense gameplay, strategic depth, and vibrant community have kept me coming back year after year, and I have no doubt that I will continue to play and enjoy this game for many more years to come. If you're looking for a game that will challenge you, engage you, and keep you coming back for more, then CS:GO is definitely the game for you.

IMPORTANT NOTE: ONLY PLAY WITH PRIME

I made a second account to see how the game is without prime. here are some of the first thins i noticed:

- If you're playing in the EU servers, most of your team mates will not speak English and/or will be very hostile
     - As much as i hate to stereotype, this involves mostly Russian players.
- You will encounter a lot of cheaters
- You will not be able to level up or play ranked

With prime:
- You will be able to level up
- You will be able to play ranked
- More English speaking people
- Less cheaters (but still a few)
- More communication and team play
- A more tactical experience as you have to know maps and line-ups

Both:
- Fun community maps
- Events where you can earn badges if you get the pass
- Dangerzone (Battle Royale)

Summary:
If you've got some friends to play with or know some Russian, it's very do-able and you can spend a lot of fun hours in here. But if you don't intent of getting Prime, it's not worth your time.

CSGO, a game that holds a special place in my heart. When I first encountered CSGO for the first time at a young age I instantly fell in love with it. I had played other shooters and this one was something different to me. It was fast paced, but balanced. It was not one of those games a brain dead person could excel at, it was perfection. I have played CSGO for years now on different accounts and although it is always the same basic idea, every match I have played was different. CSGO is one of the few rare games I have played were I never get bored of it, I always find myself coming back to it. I have gone though weeks of terrible performance yet I still find pleasure in the game. CSGO is the game that never dies, because the community cannot let this game go. It is too perfect, the best FPS ever created. For those of you who are wondering whether to play this game or buying prime, you should do it. Even with cheaters, you will still come back to this game and to me, this game is priceless.

Alright, listen up folks! If you're looking for a game that'll test your patience, make you scream in agony, and question your life choices, then CS:GO is the one for you!

This game is like a rollercoaster ride. You start off all excited, but soon you're screaming "WHY GOD, WHY?!" as you get shot in the head for the hundredth time. And don't even get me started on the teammates. You're either stuck with a bunch of bots who don't know the difference between a gun and a banana, or you're playing against a team of cyborgs who've been playing this game since before they were born.

And let's talk about the maps, shall we? One minute you're in a cozy little corner, feeling all safe and snug, and the next thing you know, you're blown to bits by a grenade. It's like the game is out to get you. Oh, and did I mention the smoke grenades? Yeah, they're a real treat. Just when you think you've got a clear shot, BAM, you're blind as a bat and stumbling around like a drunken sailor.

But you know what the best part is? You keep coming back for more. It's like a sick addiction. You tell yourself "just one more round" and before you know it, it's 3am and you're sitting there in your pajamas, covered in cheetos dust, wondering where your life went wrong.

In conclusion, if you want to experience the ultimate frustration, CS:GO is the game for you. Just don't say I didn't warn you.

The ghosts of the Global War on Terror continue to haunt us. What was the justification for invasion? Where were the weapons of mass destruction? How did Colin Powell deliver such a speech before the United Nations, the supposed protectors of the world, as to encourage skeptical nations to join the war effort? 

These questions ring hollow into the night that is Counter-Strike: Global Offensive. I wish to critique two elements of the game's title: "Global" and "Offensive." While they are mutually constitutive, each has meaning considered in its own light, and they join together to form the signifier for what we consider to be a "Counter-Strike."

First, on the meaning of Global. In Counter-Strike, the terrorists never change. Each member of the terrorist team is a player model we've seen before - grown accustomed to, even. It becomes hard to distinguish individuality or unique character among the enemy, and soon they simply assume the form of "T side," and their content becomes irrelevant. Where are they from? Who are they? These questions remain elusive, but one can use their imagination. The people that are trying to kill us in this game are nameless specters from the Middle East, nameless save for the ability of players to set Steam profile names like "dildo baggins." We fight an enemy without substance, an enemy that never changes and has no important features to be aware of save its hostility toward us. "Bomb planted" occupies the same mental imaginary of a terrorist attack. The counter-terrorists' portrayal in the game also problematizes the meaning of "Global." They can be Americans, British, French, any member of the coalition that, in the "real world," helped the United States achieve its sinister aims. They use weapons manufactured by other collaborators in the West. We can distinguish between the "good guys," but we cannot crack the code of the terrorist morphology. "Global" becomes reified in the context of UN and NATO coalitions - and this game perpetuates the virtuality of international cooperation, papering over the suspicious circumstances of that ominous invasion we all know.

Second, on the meaning of "Offensive." The threat that the terrorist constitutes in the Western imaginary justifies a response that is pro-active and requires nothing to respond to - a response without cause except for the initial cause which serves as a blank check to go on the "Offensive" ad infinitum. This game becomes  a war between good and evil, where the terrorists are reeling in the face of a counter-terrorist onslaught. How can they compete with the M4A1-S? Why do they always lose pistol round? A false narrative of violence and extremism allows the counter-terrorist to marshal the technological prowess of the West in his "Offensive" against the amorphous terrorists.

This is to say that the supposedly "Global" character of this "Offensive" is legitimate because of its "Global" nature (coalitions grant legitimacy), and the "Offensive" is a natural conclusion of the agglomeration of these Western interests in response to the initial attack against the Western nerve center in the United States. The West is like a body, and white blood cells race to the scene in international bodies to repair the damage and avenge sevenfold. This is the "Counter-Strike" - the united, noble, and pro-active front against a body of people that have no names and no choice but to perpetuate the roles that the West has permanently ascribed onto them.

In the immortal words of George W. Bush: "Now watch this drive."

Matchmaking is a toss-up depending on the time and day you que up. There is really no system to ban bad-griefing teammates, so you will most likely end up with them on your team for multiple sessions. The case drops seem to favor random people throughout the year, so hopefully you can benefit from them while you can. I believe its called a "hot streak". There are still a ton of cheaters who wall, or ghost, depending on the circumstances, and there are even boosters from overseas which carry 3-4 bad teammates at once with their "enhanced" abilities on a throwaway smurf account. CSGO passes the time, but needs to implement better anti-cheat as seen on their competitor platforms or they will lose more of the FPS market than they already have. 64 tick servers also see a lot of reg problems.

Valve's Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS: GO) debuted in 2012, backed by a strong heritage of multiplayer FPS titles, including the original Counter-Strike and Counter-Strike: Source. Now, six years later, the fast-paced PC game still mostly holds its own against more modern titles, partly because of its established core gameplay and active community. Visually, however, CS: GO is starting to show its age and it's not as thematically rich as other popular titles, such as Overwatch. Still, many players will enjoy CS: GO's no-frills experience and competitive scene, especially now that it is free to play.

So, how does CS: GO retain its prominent role in an industry that has diversified considerably since 2012? A big part of its success is due to its massive esports following. It's always among the top titles streaming on Twitch and Mixer, and it benefits from a well-established (and financially lucrative) competitive scene. The game even includes a dedicated Watch section so you can follow and spectate tournaments.

CS: GO is now free to play after a recent update. Its previous $14.99 cost was not expensive, but this price change opens the game to an even wider audience than before. In comparison, Overwatch costs $39.99, Player Unknown's Battlegrounds (PUBG) costs $29.99, and Ubisoft charges $14.99 for the Starter Edition of Rainbow Six Siege. Fortnite is, of course, free as well.

How to get started


To play CS: GO, you first need to download it from Steam. CS: GO requires a minimum of 15GB, which is relatively compact compared with most modern games' storage requirements. For comparison, Overwatch demands 30GB of disk space for installation and Fortnite takes up 20GB.

CS: GO's new Panorama menu UI is now enabled by default for all users. This interface change is highly welcome and a complete rework of the game's navigation. Gone are the confusing and unnecessarily taxing menu systems. Instead, the important options live in a neat stack of icons on the left-hand side of the screen. On the other side, you can see which of your friends are online. The middle section, like many other competitive games, now shows an overview of upcoming events on one side and your in-game character on the other. Displaying the character seems like an unnecessary use of resources, but otherwise, the Panorama update does make the experience feel a bit quicker and fluid. The simplified design language extends to many other in-game elements, including in-match leaderboards and the inventory selection screen.

Gameplay

The standard game mode (Bomb Scenario) involves either defending or exploiting a bomb site. I spent most of my test-play time playing this mode, but I did branch out to the Arms Race and Hostage modes. Most competitive matches that I've watched stick with the Bomb Scenario match type, as well, which is another reason for the mode's popularity.

The Bomb Scenario mode comprises a maximum of 15 elimination-style rounds that last until one side wins a majority of the rounds. Players spawn either on the Terrorist (T) or Counter-Terrorists (CT) side, which determines the objective. Terrorists need to plant a bomb at one of the two marked bomb sites on the map. The CT team must prevent the terrorists from planting the bomb or defuse it before it explodes (the bomb has a countdown timer of 40 seconds). The defuse process itself takes 5 seconds, so getting to the bomb site quickly is a priority. Of course, eliminating all the players on the other side makes this objective easier, so keep an eye out for enemies at all times.

CS: GO's Bomb Scenario mode is a simple, yet enjoyable, twist on the standard multiplayer FPS setup, which opens up a ton of variability in each round. Another game mode, called Hostage, flips the tables and has the Terrorists defend a hostage, while the Counter-Terrorists attempt a rescue mission. CS: GO typically gets new mission-based modes with new operations. The current operation, Operation Hydra (released in May 2017) brought War Games, Wingman, and Weapons Expert modes to the game. These modes introduce twists on regular gameplay and affect the available weapons, the match objective, and the playable maps. These operations typically include a narrative-driven campaign, too.

CS:GO is a classic and timeless first-person shooter that has stood the test of time. Its simple gameplay mechanics and competitive nature make it a must-play for any FPS fan.

The game's competitive matchmaking system is one of the best out there, providing players with a fair and balanced experience. The game's ranking system ensures that players are matched up against others with a similar skill level, making each match an exciting and challenging experience.

The game's gunplay is precise and satisfying, with a wide variety of weapons to choose from. Each weapon feels unique and has its own strengths and weaknesses, making it important to choose the right tool for the job. The game's mechanics, such as spray patterns and recoil control, add an extra layer of depth to the gameplay and provide a sense of progression as players improve their skills.

CS:GO's esports scene is also something to behold. With a dedicated community and regular tournaments, the game has cemented itself as a top-tier competitive game. Watching professional players strategize and execute their plans is thrilling, and it's a testament to the game's longevity and skill ceiling.

However, the game is not without its flaws. The game's community can be toxic at times, with players often resorting to abusive language and unsportsmanlike behavior. Additionally, the game's aging graphics and lack of new content updates can make it feel stale at times.

Overall, CS:GO is a must-play for any FPS fan looking for a competitive and challenging experience. Its simplicity and depth make it a game that you can come back to time and time again, and its esports scene ensures that there will always be something exciting to watch.

Shortly after my 50th birthday, Hank came to me with a rather, shocking proposition. He asked that I use my Live2D knowledge to recruit talents, which he would then hire using his connections in the Japanese utaite world. Connections that he made through his career with Niconico. I was... astounded, I... I always thought that Hank was a very moral man and I was... thrown, confused, but I was also particularly vulnerable at the time, something he knew and took advantage of. I was reeling from a cancer diagnosis that was poised to bankrupt my family. Hank took me on a ride along, and showed me just how much money even a small indie channel could make. And I was weak. I didn't want my family to go into financial ruin so I agreed. Every day, I think back at that moment with regret. I quickly realized that I was in way over my head, and Hank had a partner, a man named Motoaki "Yagoo" Tanigo, a businessman. Hank essentially sold me into servitude to this man, and when I tried to quit, Yagoo threatened my family. I didn't know where to turn. Eventually, Hank and Yagoo had a falling out. From what I can gather, Hank was always pushing for a greater share of the business, to which Yagoo flatly refused to give him, and things escalated. Yagoo was able to arrange, uh I guess I guess you call it a "hit" on my brother-in-law, and failed, but Hank was seriously injured, and I wound up paying his medical bills which amounted to a little over $177,000. Upon recovery, Hank was bent on revenge, working with a man named Riku Tazumi , he plotted to kill Yagoo, and did so. In fact, the bomb that he used was built by me, and he gave me no option in it. I have often contemplated suicide, but I'm a coward. I wanted to go to the police, but I was frightened. Hank had risen in the ranks to become the head of the Cover Corp, and about that time, to keep me in line, he took my children from me. For 3 months he kept them. My wife, who up until that point, had no idea of my vtubing activities, was horrified to learn what I had done, why Hank had taken our children. We were scared. I was in Hell, I hated myself for what I had brought upon my family. Recently, I tried once again to quit, to end this nightmare, and in response, he gave me this. I can't take this anymore. I live in fear every day that Hank will kill me, or worse, hurt my family. I... All I could think to do was to make this video in hope that the world will finally see this man, for what he really is.

I am a 50 year old father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game.
I am a single father for my son who is now 14 years old. My son has recently started playing Counter-Strike: Global Offensive.
In less than a week, he has already played more than 20 hours.
It was terrible for me, because it was already hard enough for me to spend time with my son.
because he was always with his friends or watching YouTube videos.
So I decided to create a Steam account to play with my son. I started playing but it was my first time playing a video game since the 90s so I was pretty lost. I asked my son for help and we spent several hours together playing this game.
I liked it as it was the best time I have had with my son since my wife died. Playing video games reminded me that there is fun in everything and it brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside of the house.

I am a 50 year old father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game.
I am a single father for my son who is now 14 years old. My son has recently started playing CS:GO.
In less than a week, he has already played more than 20 hours.
It was terrible for me, because it was already hard enough for me to spend time with my son.
because he was always with his friends or watching YouTube videos.
So I decided to create a Steam account to play with my son. I started playing but it was my first time playing a video game since the 90s so I was pretty lost. I asked my son for help and we spent several hours together playing this game.
I liked it as it was the best time I have had with my son since my wife died. Playing video games reminded me that there is fun in everything and it brought me and my son closer again and now we actually spend time together outside of the house.

Unfortunately while trying to copy Valorant they've done nothing unique from Valorant and even do several things worse on a technical level, which I assume might be because of what seems like a poorly optimised and dated engine.

If you're looking for a game that will test your reflexes, strategic thinking, and patience with Russian players, then CS:GO is the game for you. It's like playing chess, but with guns and angry teenagers from Siberia. But don't let the language barrier discourage you, because there's nothing quite like the feeling of clutching a round and hearing your teammates scream 'cyka blyat' in celebration. Just make sure you have a good pair of headphones to protect your eardrums from the sound of your teammates screaming into their microphones like they're auditioning for a death metal band. In short, CS:GO is a game that will both challenge you and make you question your sanity, but it's all worth it for the sweet taste of victory (and vodka)

One of the things that sets CS:GO apart from other shooters is its emphasis on teamwork and strategy. Communication is key, and players must work together to coordinate attacks, defend objectives, and outmaneuver their opponents. This makes for an engaging and dynamic experience that never gets old.

The graphics and sound design in CS:GO are top-notch, with realistic weapon models and immersive sound effects that really bring the game to life. The game's replayability is also impressive, with a strong esports scene that provides endless opportunities for players to improve their skills and compete at the highest levels.

(CS:GO) is an incredibly fun and engaging first-person shooter game that has captivated gamers worldwide.

One of the most impressive aspects of CS:GO is its game-play. The game requires strategic thinking, quick reflexes, and excellent aim. Players must work together in teams to achieve objectives and defeat their opponents, making it an excellent game for those who enjoy cooperative play.

The game's graphics are also impressive, with detailed maps and character models that make the game feel immersive and realistic. The sound effects are also well-designed, adding to the overall experience of playing the game.

In addition to its excellent gameplay and graphics, CS:GO has a thriving community of players and a competitive scene that makes it a popular choice for those who enjoy esports. This community has created a variety of game modes, custom maps, and mods that keep the game fresh and exciting.

cream pie

1. Cut the vanilla bean down the middle and open the pod. Use your knife to scrape out the seeds, then mix them into the milk in a small pot. Set over medium heat and bring almost to a boil. Set aside to cool for about 10 minutes or so. The pod can be added to your sugar canister to make vanilla sugar!

2. Whisk the 2 eggs and 2 yolks in a medium bowl and set aside. You can use the extra egg whites for a meringue or use them in they morning omelette. 



Two photos showing milk pouring into a pot and eggs getting tempered.
3. Whisk the dry ingredients together in a medium pot then add the scalded milk (use a strainer if there are stray vanilla bean pod pieces mixed in) and whisk again. Cook over medium-high heat until thickened while whisking continuously.

4. Gradually add a cup of the hot milk mixture into the beaten eggs to temper them. This warms the eggs so they don‚Äôt scramble when added to the pot.

Two photos showingCustard being made for a cream pie.


5. Add the tempered egg mixture back into the pot while whisking. Cook and stir on medium heat for an additional 2 minutes.

6. Remove pot from heat and stir in butter then mix until dissolved. If you‚Äôre using vanilla extract you will add it in with the butter.

Two photos showing custard being chilled then transferred to a Pie crust.
7. Transfer custard to a bowl and cover with plastic and chill to bring to room temp.

8. Add the cooled custard to the pie shell and smooth with a spatula.

Two photos showing cream being whipped then piped onto a cream pie.


9. Whip the cold cream with sugar and vanilla until soft peaks form.

10. Add whipped cream onto the chilled pie. I piped little rosettes with a medium closed star tip but you can just pile a big mound on top xx

My name is Walter Hartwell White. I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104. This is my confession. If you're watching this tape, I'm probably dead, murdered by my brother-in-law Hank Schrader. Hank has been building a meth empire for over a year now and using me as his chemist. Shortly after my 50th birthday, Hank came to me with a rather, shocking proposition. He asked that I use my chemistry knowledge to cook methamphetamine, which he would then sell using his connections in the drug world. Connections that he made through his career with the DEA. I was... astounded, I... I always thought that Hank was a very moral man and I was... thrown, confused, but I was also particularly vulnerable at the time, something he knew and took advantage of. I was reeling from a cancer diagnosis that was poised to bankrupt my family. Hank took me on a ride along, and showed me just how much money even a small meth operation could make. And I was weak. I didn't want my family to go into financial ruin so I agreed. Every day, I think back at that moment with regret. I quickly realized that I was in way over my head, and Hank had a partner, a man named Gustavo Fring, a businessman. Hank essentially sold me into servitude to this man, and when I tried to quit, Fring threatened my family. I didn't know where to turn.
Eventually, Hank and Fring had a falling out. From what I can gather, Hank was always pushing for a greater share of the business, to which Fring flatly refused to give him, and things escalated. Fring was able to arrange, uh I guess I guess you call it a "hit" on my brother-in-law, and failed, but Hank was seriously injured, and I wound up paying his medical bills which amounted to a little over $177,000. Upon recovery, Hank was bent on revenge, working with a man named Hector Salamanca, he plotted to kill Fring, and did so. In fact, the bomb that he used was built by me, and he gave me no option in it. I have often contemplated suicide, but I'm a coward. I wanted to go to the police, but I was frightened. Hank had risen in the ranks to become the head of the Albuquerque DEA, and about that time, to keep me in line, he took my children from me. For 3 months he kept them. My wife, who up until that point, had no idea of my criminal activities, was horrified to learn what I had done, why Hank had taken our children. We were scared. I was in Hell, I hated myself for what I had brought upon my family. Recently, I tried once again to quit, to end this nightmare, and in response, he gave me this. I can't take this anymore. I live in fear every day that Hank will kill me, or worse, hurt my family. I... All I could think to do was to make this video in hope that the world will finally see this man, for what he really is.

Counter-Strike:Global Offensive, Ahhhh, There is a lot to talk about this game. I would want to go fast about this review so:
I've been playing Counter-Strike franchise for a a long time now, and i want to write my *Honest* opinion.
Counter-Strike Are Great Games And I Totaly Recomend Giving Them A Try If You Love First-Person Shooters.
Now For Especialy CS:GO. The Game Is Great, As The Other, BUT It Lacks A Lot Of The Good Mechanics Which The Older Games Have.
1. I really wished the cs:go movement was the same as one in cs 1.6. Yes the movement in the game is great and you can really make nice bhops and jumps but i think the bunnyhops and more were better in cs 1.6
2. If you play offline(with no friends,group, etc.), its 99% chance to meet a lot of russains, which for my opinions its funny but annoying at the same time(Please Valve Change The Region. I dont want to play with russians 24/7)
3. Toxic Players - Yea, um i said about russians but they are not the only ones. There're a lot of toxic players so have that in mind. I just recommend playing with friend/friends
4. "Hackers" - Do i have to say more? To Peope Who Are New. Hackers Are Always Around In Every Lobby(Especially if you dont have prime bought), So Have This In Mind :)
Positive:
1. As people say "This game is easy: To Get Used To, But Hard To Master", and its true. You need a lot of training to get good, which makes the game matchmaking which is good (because no one wants to play with 9year old kids which  shouts every 2 seconds)
2. As I Said There Mechanics Which I Don't Like In CS:GO, BUT There are a lot of others which i like:
1.Progress.
2. The Nice People In The Game. Yes there are a lot, but when i mean a lot, a lot of toxic players but if you luck you may find some good players
3.Skins - I mean? What more to say
There are A lot more but i can't fit them all here so yea, here you go :D

Idk If Anyone Will Give The Time To Read This "Review" Of Mine, But To Those Who Did.
<3 Thank you.
And i hope i helped newer player to think twice if they want to play the game.

This game saved my life.

I am 45.

My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and adopted our son together. They are now both 4 years old.

When we were going through our separation, I found myself lost and miserable. I was self destructive. I got so mad one day from everything spiralling out of my control that I punched some concrete in a moment of overwhelming emotion. That caused me to break my 5th metacarpal in my right hand... my working hand... my games hand.. the hand that I held and carried my children to bed with.. The hand I desperately needed to make sure I could continue to provide.

After learning of the severity of my self-inflicted damage, I was borderline suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man with no history of depression or anxiety. I have never had fits of rage, or been one to break down and cry, but I was in a low spot that just really buried me from being able to see the light on the other side.

Having nothing better to do, I searched for a game I could play, ONE HANDED while I recovered. I somehow stumbled upon this game and read some of the reviews. I decided that it had to be worth a shot... I must admit, I didn't beat the game, or play nearly as long as some of you. In fact, I may have only played this game a day or two.. With that being said, after doing so, I had a new found joy and hope for life. I was able to put behind me the pain and suffering that had been cast over me. I was able to experience other peoples joy and happiness. I was able to see the fruits of my "labor". I relaxed for 5 ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô• minutes to this music long enough to realize that I was going to be okay.

After coming to that realization, I turned the game off, and I went back to work. It hurt my hand like hell but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so damn sorry for myself, and I became the father I needed to be in that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving as.

Today, I am close friend with my kids mother. We don't fight, or argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents, and friends.

I now have 3 kids. My third child is, wait for it, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my own separation, and we just stumbled in to each others life unexpectedly. We have been in a relationship for a year now, and are very happy together.

Moral of the story, you never know what life holds in store for you, and if I would have given up when all the odds were stacked against me, I wouldn't be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.

Counter Strike Global Offensive is a game developed by Valve.
It is extremely difficult, considering you have to wrangle teammates, manage your economy, predict your enemies economy, buy the correct ‚ô•‚ô•‚ô•‚ô• and then aim for the head and spray correctly.

There's a story that someone was so good with his mouse that he became the mouse.
The mouse permanently fused into his hand. Now he has to use his other hand for certain things.

The game has multiple maps, including dust 2 which is the only map, and Mirage. But mirage...really isn't working these days.

Not many people know that every decoy grenade is sent from the deepest circles of hell, where the souls of the damned are burned and seared alive for all eternity.

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive is like the ultimate test of patience and trigger discipline. It's a game where one shot can mean the difference between victory and defeat, and where split-second decisions can make or break a round. And the stakes are high, because no one wants to be the one to let their team down.

But despite the pressure, there's still room for humor. From the colorful cast of characters you can play as to the ridiculous shenanigans that can occur in-game, there's always something to laugh about. And let's not forget about the memes and inside jokes that have formed within the community over the years.

And the best part? No matter how many times you die, you can always respawn and try again. So if you're up for a challenge and want to test your skills against some of the best players in the world, then CS:GO is the game for you. Just don't be surprised if you end up losing your voice from shouting at your monitor.

I have no intentions of reviewing CS:GO, but I want to share my Hardtack Recipe (Survival Bread). That is all.

-Preheat oven to 375 degrees F.

-Mix the flour, water and salt in a bowl.

-After mixing completely, the dough should be a little dry (and not stick to your fingers).
If your mix is still too sticky, you can add more flour in small increments until the dough is dry enough.
Use a roller to spread out the dough on a counter, large cutting board, etc. until it reaches a thickness of roughly 1/3 to 1/2 inches.

-To prevent sticking to the counter or cutting board, you should spread a little flour on the surface before rolling the dough. Also spread a little flour on top of the dough to prevent the roller from sticking to the dough.
Cut the dough into squares (i.e. 3 inch squares). You can create square hardtack ‚Äúbiscuits‚Äù by cutting the dough horizontally & vertically on a large cutting board.

-Poke narrow holes in the hardtack biscuits with a chopstick or fork. The holes should go all the way through to the other side of the hardtack. This prevents the hardtack from puffing up.
Place the hardtack biscuits on a baking sheet/tray.

-Put the baking sheet into the oven and bake for 30 minutes. Wear oven mitts.
Flip the hardtack over with a spatula and bake for another 30 minutes. Wear oven mitts.
Remove the baking sheet from the oven. Wear oven mitts. Then use a spatula to remove the hardtack from the baking sheet. Place the hardtack biscuits on a cooling rack in order to cool down.
When completely cooled, place the hardtack in an airtight container.

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) is a first-person shooter game. Despite its popularity, the game has faced criticism due to the persistent issue of cheating.

Valve Corporation, the developers of CS:GO, have implemented various anti-cheat measures such as Valve Anti-Cheat (VAC) and Overwatch to detect and ban cheaters. However, it is still common for players to encounter cheaters in their games, and some players feel that the developers have not done enough to effectively address this issue.

Cheating can severely impact the player experience in CS:GO, making it difficult to enjoy the game and compete fairly. This can be especially frustrating for players who have invested time and effort into the game.

Based on the persistent issue of cheating in Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO), I would not recommend playing this game. While the developers have made attempts to address the issue, it remains a major problem that can significantly impact the player experience. If you are looking for a fair and enjoyable first-person shooter game, there may be other options available that are better suited to your needs.

Getting Started
To play CS: GO, you first need to download it from Steam. CS: GO requires a minimum of 15GB, which is relatively compact compared with most modern games' storage requirements. For comparison, Overwatch demands 30GB of disk space for installation and Fortnite takes up 20GB.

CS: GO's new Panorama menu UI is now enabled by default for all users. This interface change is highly welcome and a complete rework of the game's navigation. Gone are the confusing and unnecessarily taxing menu systems. Instead, the important options live in a neat stack of icons on the left-hand side of the screen. On the other side, you can see which of your friends are online. The middle section, like many other competitive games, now shows an overview of upcoming events on one side and your in-game character on the other. Displaying the character seems like an unnecessary use of resources, but otherwise, the Panorama update does make the experience feel a bit quicker and fluid. The simplified design language extends to many other in-game elements, including in-match leaderboards and the inventory selection screen.

Gameplay
The standard game mode (Bomb Scenario) involves either defending or exploiting a bomb site. I spent most of my test-play time playing this mode, but I did branch out to the Arms Race and Hostage modes. Most competitive matches that I've watched stick with the Bomb Scenario match type, as well, which is another reason for the mode's popularity.

The Bomb Scenario mode comprises a maximum of 15 elimination-style rounds that last until one side wins a majority of the rounds. Players spawn either on the Terrorist (T) or Counter-Terrorists (CT) side, which determines the objective. Terrorists need to plant a bomb at one of the two marked bomb sites on the map. The CT team must prevent the terrorists from planting the bomb or defuse it before it explodes (the bomb has a countdown timer of 40 seconds). The defuse process itself takes 5 seconds, so getting to the bomb site quickly is a priority. Of course, eliminating all the players on the other side makes this objective easier, so keep an eye out for enemies at all times.

CS: GO's Bomb Scenario mode is a simple, yet enjoyable, twist on the standard multiplayer FPS setup, which opens up a ton of variability in each round. Another game mode, called Hostage, flips the tables and has the Terrorists defend a hostage, while the Counter-Terrorists attempt a rescue mission. CS: GO typically gets new mission-based modes with new operations. The current operation, Operation Hydra (released in May 2017) brought War Games, Wingman, and Weapons Expert modes to the game. These modes introduce twists on regular gameplay and affect the available weapons, the match objective, and the playable maps. These operations typically include a narrative-driven campaign, too.

Danger Zone
Along with making the game free to play, Valve added a battle royale mode called Danger Zone. CS: GO's take on this latest gaming craze is much smaller in scale than that of Fortnite and PUBG. Instead of the typical 100-player matches, solo matches are restricted to just 16 players and team modes are capped at 18 total players. The map size is also much smaller than those in either of the other titles. After a brief warmup period, players get to choose a spawn point on the map. Each drop point is limited to a single player, so make sure you choose your preferred spot quickly. Matches unfold in much the same way as in any other battle royale game. Your goal is to eliminate all the other enemy players or teams. You must scavenge for weapons, avoid taking damage from the random bombings, and keep pace with the ever-closing boundaries of the play area.

That said, CS: GO does bring some unique mechanics to the genre. For example, as the match progresses, you can purchase weapons and items, which are delivered by drone to your location. Be aware that these drone deliveries can reveal your hiding spot, though. Another cool mechanic is the in-game map that highlights the regions where either you or enemy players are located. The map is not detailed enough to give away specific locations, but the information it provides is helpful for planning your next movements. CS: GO also has the upper hand in terms of combat mechanics. Weapons and movement especially feel more accurate than in Fortnite and PUBG.

All these factors make for a much more condensed and manageable experience. I particularly enjoy that matches tend to only take about 10 minutes from start to finish. In terms of potential improvements, I would like to see a few additional maps and gameplay variations, such as a one-on-one mode or an eight-person team mode.

Maps
Which CS: GO maps you can play depends largely on the game mode. Regardless, you should try to familiarize yourself with as many as possible, if you care at all about strategy or coordinating with your teammates. There's no worse in-game feeling of being the last one on your team alive and frantically trying to find the bomb site in time while your teammates watch (and judge) you. All maps have a couple of different paths, clearly marked bomb sites, and recognizable features, so it shouldn't be too difficult to get up to speed.

CS: GO hosts a large number of official maps; despite my 50-plus hours into the game, I have not encountered all of them through regular play. For example, the Casual mode currently lists four different playlists of maps: Sigma (Austria, Shipped, Train, Overpass, Nuke, and Canals), Delta (Mirage, Inferno, Cache, and Cobble), Dust II (Dust II) and Hostage Group (Agency, Insertion, Office, Italy, and Assault). Variety is always appreciated, but I feel like some maps don't receive the same level of attention as others. Dust II is probably the best-known map. Some form of this iconic map has been in every Counter-Strike title to date, and it's a heavy favorite in player voting at the end of matches. There's nothing wrong with the map, but playing it over and over again can get stale after a while. I appreciate that Valve has moved Dust II to its own playlist in casual modes. Maps are frequently added and dropped from the playable lists though, so your experience may vary.

Weapons, Equipment, and Combat
When I first started playing CS: GO, I was confused by the weapon purchase system at the beginning of each round, and I suspect most newcomers will feel the same way. Basically, at the beginning of each round, you have a certain amount of money to purchase weapons and other equipment for the round. In the first round, you only have enough cash on hand to buy a pistol and one other item (I talk about equipment a bit later). During the round, you earn additional cash by eliminating enemies and, of course, for your team winning the round. The losing side also gets some cash, but the cost of multiple weapons, grenades, and other equipment quickly adds up, so winning teams and skilled players will have the tactical advantage. In later rounds, players on both sides have more than enough cash to buy multiple weapons and items.

Terrorists and Counter-Terrorists have access to most of the same weapons, and the ones that are different are balanced with each other. CS: GO organizes weapons by type: pistols, shotguns, submachine guns, rifles, and machine guns. Generally, the more powerful the gun, the more it costs. However, don't simply buy a weapon because it's the most expensive one. Take some time to experiment and find a loadout that works for you. You can carry up to two guns (a pistol and something else), which is always a good idea, for those times you are caught by an enemy mid-reload. There are also quite a few fan favorites, such as the "Deagle" (Desert Eagle pistol) or the AWP (a powerful sniper rifle) that tend to make an appearance in most matches.

"I am a 52 year old father, probably one of the oldest people playing this game. I am a single father to my son, who is now 16. My son recently started Dinkum and in less than a week, he had already played for over 20 hours. This was terrible for me, as it was already hard enough for me to spend time with my son, as he is always out with his friends or just watching videos on Tiktok. So I decided to make a Steam account and get this game to see if I could maybe play alongside him. I loaded into the game, did the tutorial but I was stuck on what you where supposed to do. I asked my Son for help and he hosted a game for me to join. I loved it as it was the best time I had spent with my Son since my wife had died. CSGO, a game that holds a special place in my heart. When I first encountered CSGO for the first time at a young age(im sad to say it was the roblox version) I instantly fell in love with it. CSGO is one of the few rare games I have played were I never get bored of it, I always find myself coming back to it. I have gone though weeks of terrible performance yet I still find pleasure in the game. CSGO is the game that never dies, because the community cannot let this game go. Mainly, this game is a sort of game that has a HIGH skill ceiling, with basically infinite ways to win a round, win a game, get a ace, breach a site, retake, you name it. Best game for fps lovers out there. Just give the game a try, stick with it, and you'll see results VERY quickly.

Only problem i'd see here is finding out which role you are in a CS team. here's the basics:
If your a leader (or a person who likes making calls) than the role of an IGL is for you. IGL is mainly to group with someone and support the team with calls and information.

If you have fast reaction, can flick well, and like skill based weapons, than the class of a sniper is for you. Your goal is to mainly hold an open area (like middle on most maps). In the beginning of sniping, id suggest using an auto sniper (SCAR-20 AND G3SG) and then upgrading to the Scout (ssg 08) and the AWP.

If you like rushing than the role of (captain obvious) a rusher is for you. these guys, well, rush. the optimal choice for rushers are PDWs (SMGs),  (Not the P90, P90 is only useful in the first 4 rounds) and the Rifle category.
(oh, btw, Valve has some good guns rated lower than they should, like the FAMAS, MAC-10, UMP, MP-9, and the MAG-7 and SAWED OFF)

The last role is support, they usually use guns from the heavy category (Negev, Mag-7/Sawed Off) and they full utility (Smokes, molotovs, and flashbangs). They smoke off entrances, throw molotovs in common positions, and flashbang the site before entry. They go with the rusher, providing support for any close range encounters.

My name is Walter Hartwell White. I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104. This is my confession. If you're watching this tape, I'm probably dead, murdered by my brother-in-law Hank Schrader. Hank has been building a meth empire for over a year now and using me as his chemist. Shortly after my 50th birthday, Hank came to me with a rather, shocking proposition. He asked that I use my chemistry knowledge to cook methamphetamine, which he would then sell using his connections in the drug world. Connections that he made through his career with the DEA. I was... astounded, I... I always thought that Hank was a very moral man and I was... thrown, confused, but I was also particularly vulnerable at the time, something he knew and took advantage of. I was reeling from a cancer diagnosis that was poised to bankrupt my family. Hank took me on a ride along, and showed me just how much money even a small meth operation could make. And I was weak. I didn't want my family to go into financial ruin so I agreed. Every day, I think back at that moment with regret. I quickly realized that I was in way over my head, and Hank had a partner, a man named Gustavo Fring, a businessman. Hank essentially sold me into servitude to this man, and when I tried to quit, Fring threatened my family. I didn't know where to turn. Eventually, Hank and Fring had a falling out. From what I can gather, Hank was always pushing for a greater share of the business, to which Fring flatly refused to give him, and things escalated. Fring was able to arrange, uh I guess I guess you call it a "hit" on my brother-in-law, and failed, but Hank was seriously injured, and I wound up paying his medical bills which amounted to a little over $177,000. Upon recovery, Hank was bent on revenge, working with a man named Hector Salamanca, he plotted to kill Fring, and did so. In fact, the bomb that he used was built by me, and he gave me no option in it. I have often contemplated suicide, but I'm a coward. I wanted to go to the police, but I was frightened. Hank had risen in the ranks to become the head of the Albuquerque DEA, and about that time, to keep me in line, he took my children from me. For 3 months he kept them. My wife, who up until that point, had no idea of my criminal activities, was horrified to learn what I had done, why Hank had taken our children. We were scared. I was in Hell, I hated myself for what I had brought upon my family. Recently, I tried once again to quit, to end this nightmare, and in response, he gave me this. I can't take this anymore. I live in fear every day that Hank will kill me, or worse, hurt my family. I... All I could think to do was to make this video in hope that the world will finally see this man, for what he really is.

because he was always with his friends or watching YouTube videos.

As a gamer, I have spent many hours playing Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) and I can say that it is one of the best online multiplayer first-person shooter games available.

One of the key aspects of CS:GO that sets it apart from other shooters is its emphasis on strategy and teamwork. Whether playing in casual or competitive modes, success in CS:GO requires coordination with your teammates and a well-thought-out plan. The game also has a strong sense of replayability, with constantly changing objectives and situations that keep the gameplay fresh and engaging.

Another aspect of CS:GO that I appreciate is the wide range of customization options available for weapons and player models. This allows players to personalize their experience and add an extra level of expression to their gameplay.

The game also has a thriving competitive scene, with regular tournaments and events that draw in top-level players from all around the world. This, combined with the high skill ceiling of the game, means that there is always room for growth and improvement for dedicated players.

In conclusion, CS:GO is an outstanding game that I would highly recommend to any fan of first-person shooters or online multiplayer games. Its emphasis on strategy, teamwork, and customization make it a truly unique experience.

Ah, Counter-Strike Global Offensive, the shooter that just won't die! This game has been around for nearly a decade, and it's still going strong. However, one of its biggest drawbacks is the rampant cheating that goes on in the game.

The graphics in CS:GO are pretty solid, with weapons that look and feel weighty, and environments that are well-detailed. The sound design is fantastic, too - every gunshot, explosion, and ricochet feels like it has real impact.

The gameplay is what really sets CS:GO apart from other shooters. It's a tactical game that requires teamwork, strategy, and quick reflexes. You'll be constantly on edge, as a single mistake can be the difference between victory and defeat. Unfortunately, this intense atmosphere can be ruined by cheaters who use aimbots, wallhacks, and other cheating software to gain an unfair advantage. It's a shame, as this detracts from the overall experience of the game.

In conclusion, CS:GO is an absolute blast to play, but the cheating problem can be a real buzzkill. Just make sure you bring a team of friends, or you'll be in for a world of hurt! And remember: always aim for the head.

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive, or CS:GO for short, is hands down one of the most exciting and entertaining shooters on the market. It's a game that'll have you on the edge of your seat, laughing out loud, and shouting at your screen all at the same time. The game's fast-paced, first-person action is like a thrill ride that never stops, with each round bringing new challenges and surprises.

But what really sets CS:GO apart is its incredible sense of humor. From the over-the-top characters and weapons, to the absurdly funny maps and game modes, there's always something to make you chuckle. The game's developers clearly understand that sometimes a little bit of humor can go a long way in making a game more enjoyable, and they've done an amazing job at incorporating it into the core experience.

So if you're looking for a game that'll keep you entertained and laughing for hours, look no further than Counter-Strike: Global Offensive. Just be prepared to have your mouse-clicking finger ready, because this game will test your skills and keep you on your toes every step of the way.

I like csgo sometimes but honestly at his point of its existence it's just boring now. The game got forced into this ultra competitive game that relies on the opinions of the "professional" players to dictate 99% of balance decisions. All of the things that made this game fun back in the day are gone, I genuinely cannot imagine being a new csgo player (i.e. JUST getting the game in 2022/2023). If they brought back the old reserve maps into competitive it would probably be worth your time just to get a more casual experience, but it's clear that Valve doesn't really give a shit about the casual player anymore and just wants to pander to the 14-22 year old demographic of twitch watching mindless vessels who only want to play whatever Na'Vi or Astralis tells them is a "good" map. I almost guarantee by the end of 2024 we're gonna end up with the "active duty" pool being just the same boring 3 lane maps that all just have a different coat of paint. I hate that Valve actively knifed a lot of the long time fans in the back by canning all of the old maps back in 2017 with the bullshit excuse that "Oh gee we just don't have the servers available to host these maps because NO ONE plays them, but we promise we'll remake those defuse maps you guys liked so much!!!" and then only followed through with the ONE map (Vertigo), meaning that for people like me who enjoyed the older maps and hostage mode. They care so little about hostage maps that Militia has been stuck with the same shitty christmas version for almost 5 years now and they haven't bothered to change it back to the arguably great version they changed it to at the start of 2017. Just bring us back the old maps, I hate that all these players have gotten brainwashed into thinking that less map variety = good, especially when every 6 months we get 2 maps added to competitive that we all know will be removed in the next major patch, making learning them literally fucking worthless, when Valve could just as easily reinstate Dust, Militia, Aztec, Italy, and Assault (All of which already have remakes and reworks on the workshop that they could use instead if they're THAT fucking hesitant to add a map that still looks like the CSS version) and keep them in and people would probably warm up to those maps again.

PROS: Great shooter... mechanics are fun and fluid enough that you can still goof around with your friends and have a good time but it's still an INSANE competitive game. Movement is smooth and responsive, shooting feels good and you're rewarded for learning spray patterns and knowing utility. The maps are also generally well designed in my opinion. The biggest plus for me is that there is a refreshing lack of bullshit in this game compared to other shooters on the market. No stupid ass 56.7039% AOE slow abilities, no wall hack (except for cheating), no healing and no ultimate abilities etc. It's just a matter of how good you can aim and play compared to the other team. If you have the time and put in the effort to becoming decent at the game it can feel pretty rewarding...

Cons: Cheating can be a problem in matchmaking but I personally haven't run into any in the few games I've played recently, if you're worried about cheaters Faceit has a better anti cheat than matchmaking. The community is also divided between Faceit and matchmaking due to the 64 vs 128 tick debate and the different tickrate causing nade lineups to be different I don't know there's a lot about that issue. This game also isn't as accessible to new players imo as it's pretty unforgiving and utility requires practice and memory to become fully useful.

As someone who played Counter-Strike: Global Offensive, I can say that while the game has some positive elements, it also has several major flaws. The graphics and presentation are good, with detailed environments and character models, but the overall gameplay experience is marred by several issues.

One of the most notable issues with the game is its balance. Certain weapons and equipment are overpowered, leading to a lack of variety in gameplay and making it difficult for players to compete on an equal footing. Additionally, the matchmaking system can be flawed, often pairing players with others who are significantly more skilled.

Another issue with the game is its community. While some players are friendly and helpful, others are toxic and disruptive, making the game less enjoyable for everyone. This is compounded by the lack of effective moderation or enforcement from the game's developers.

Finally, the game's microtransaction system is also problematic. While cosmetic items can be earned through gameplay, many players feel that the game is designed to encourage players to spend real money on in-game items, leading to a pay-to-win dynamic that can detract from the overall experience.

Overall, while Counter-Strike: Global Offensive has some positive elements, its balance issues, toxic community, and problematic microtransaction system make it a less than ideal choice for first-person shooter fans.

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive (CS:GO) is considered a good game due to its tactical gameplay, competitive scene, wide variety of game modes, strong community, and excellent graphics and sound design. As a first-person shooter, CS:GO requires players to work together as a team, communicate effectively, and use tactics to defeat their opponents. The game has a thriving esports scene, with numerous tournaments and leagues being held throughout the year, allowing players to compete against some of the best players in the world. CS:GO offers multiple game modes, including classic bomb defusal and hostage rescue modes, as well as others like arms race, demolition, and casual. The game also has a large and dedicated player base, which has contributed to the creation of custom maps, skins, and mods, and a vibrant trading and cosmetic market. The high-quality graphics and sound design of CS:GO add to the overall immersive gaming experience, making it a well-regarded game among first-person shooter fans.

This game used to be perfect in 2013 - 2016... Something changed around the end of 2016.
The player base started to turn into this annoying community. All of the people that played seriously started to leave the normal valve matchmaking system and went off to things such as FACEIT / ESEA. That was okay though cause we were just able to make a nice switch. 
We'd be using that for our serious competitive matchmaking untillllllll there were too many trolls on FACEIT too, which forced you to buy FACEIT Premium or play with a pre-made squad.

The game never played the same anymore though, because there was this overload of cheaters and ignorant people, which completely removed the fun for the game for me... This account I'm playing on has 502 hours but I've been playing since 2013 on multiple accounts (smurfs, etc... you know the drill). Everything combined I have at least 7000-8000 hours on this game.

Was it worth it? Totally. Every day I came back from school for the past ten years CSGO was there for me. Unlike any other game, this one had a special place in my heart no matter how many toxic players/cheaters I came by. I learnt to cope with it as you should in any other title. But nowadays, for me personally, I don't see the same fun in the game anymore. I used to put all of my time into the game and even outside of the game I'd be watching all of the ESL/Big league cups, use trading websites, care about my inventory. Somehow I am just unbothered about the game nowadays, some kind of "special" feeling has been removed and I cannot properly explain it.

All I know is that the game did serve me very well but it also gave me a lot of stress, headaches and disappointment. Not due to the game itself but to the player base, it's toxic and I am sure a lot of players can agree.

Do play this game if you're seeking for a competitive shooter, but don't expect your teammates to be JUST as invested into it as you are. 50/50 chance there will be someone that's playing competitive with a casual mindset, not caring as much as the other 4 players.

Counter-Strike: Global Offensive took the long way to success. It started off with a number of significant flaws, but with time and some substantial patches, has become one of the most-played games on Steam and one of the best PC games you can play.

As usual, the people who know the game best are the ones who spend every night and most weekends in the trenches, defusing bombs, shooting chickens, and desperately hunting for knives. Also as usual, the people who love the game most are also the ones who have the most complicated relationship with it. Play a game enough, and even if you love it, part of you will probably start to loathe it. In a loving way. If that makes sense.

I've really enjoyed Patricia's semi-regular Steam Reviews roundup series, since they give a glimpse into the minds (and senses of humor) of a given game's most dedicated players. So, I thought I'd dive into the CS:GO Steam page and see what I could find.

Generally speaking: CS:GO players love the chickens, are flummoxed by the knives, are in agreement that Dust2 is in some ways the game's only map, and hate hackers almost as much as they hate being called hackers. And of course, like any good game, for all the complaints most people have, they still can't stop playing.

Get ready to dive into the world of Dust 2 and Mirage, where spray n' pray reigns the road to global!

Gameplay:
In terms of gameplay, it's like taking a crash course in the art of Russian insults. You'll be a master of "Cyka Blyat" in no time.

Graphics and Sound:
The sound design is a symphony of screams and gunfire, with a chorus of shouting Russians and pre-teens providing the beat. The graphics are about as exciting as a rainy day, but who needs sunshine when you can spend all your money on skins and show them off to your friends? Substance over style, baby!

Depth and Content:
When it comes to depth and content, this game is untouchable. From Battle Scarred to Factory New, Safari Mesh to Marble Fade, the possibilities are endless. It's like a never-ending fashion show, but with weapons instead of models

Difficulty:
CS:GO offers a range of difficulty, from newborn to demigod. Depending on your rank, you'll face opponents who are either easy picks or near-unstoppable thunderstorms. It's like a journey from crawling to sprinting, from amateur to pro. But no matter where you fall on the spectrum, the challenge will keep you coming back for more. Just remember, it's not the destination, it's the journey that counts.

Technical Issues:
CS:GO is like a smooth-sailing ship. But beware, sometimes it might feel like the Wild West when it comes to hackers. So saddle up and get ready for an unfair showdown.

Value for Money:
You might think that the game is free, but it feels mor like a free sample of crack cocaine. Before you know it, you'll be hooked and digging into your life savings to fund your case opening addiction. It's like a black hole for your wallet, sucking you in and never letting go. But hey, at least you'll have the most expensive steam inventory known to mankind, right? Just be prepared to sell your first-born child for that AWP Dragonlore you've always wanted.

Although my family now sees me as a useless disappointment, through hard work I have worked my way up to Silver 5 and can now show the ladies my impressive inventory, earned through sheer determination in gambling. I would definitely recommend the game!

Ancient manuscripts also divided sentences into paragraphs with line breaks (newline) followed by an initial at the beginning of the next paragraph. An initial is an oversized capital letter, sometimes outdented beyond the margin of the text. This style can be seen, for example, in the original Old English manuscript of Beowulf. Outdenting is still used in English typography, though not commonly.[2] Modern English typography usually indicates a new paragraph by indenting the first line. This style can be seen in the (handwritten) United States Constitution from 1787. For additional ornamentation, a hedera leaf or other symbol can be added to the inter-paragraph white space, or put in the indentation space.

A second common modern English style is to use no indenting, but add vertical white space to create "block paragraphs." On a typewriter, a double carriage return produces a blank line for this purpose; professional typesetters (or word processing software) may put in an arbitrary vertical space by adjusting leading. This style is very common in electronic formats, such as on the World Wide Web and email. Wikipedia itself employs this format.

My name is Walter Hartwell White. I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane, Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104. This is my confession. If you're watching this tape, I'm probably dead, murdered by my brother-in-law Hank Schrader. Hank has been building a meth empire for over a year now and using me as his chemist. Shortly after my 50th birthday, Hank came to me with a rather, shocking proposition. He asked that I use my chemistry knowledge to cook methamphetamine, which he would then sell using his connections in the drug world. Connections that he made through his career with the DEA. I was... astounded, I... I always thought that Hank was a very moral man and I was... thrown, confused, but I was also particularly vulnerable at the time, something he knew and took advantage of. I was reeling from a cancer diagnosis that was poised to bankrupt my family. Hank took me on a ride along, and showed me just how much money even a small meth operation could make. And I was weak. I didn't want my family to go into financial ruin so I agreed. Every day, I think back at that moment with regret. I quickly realized that I was in way over my head, and Hank had a partner, a man named Gustavo Fring, a businessman. Hank essentially sold me into servitude to this man, and when I tried to quit, Fring threatened my family. I didn't know where to turn. Eventually, Hank and Fring had a falling out. From what I can gather, Hank was always pushing for a greater share of the business, to which Fring flatly refused to give him, and things escalated. Fring was able to arrange, uh I guess I guess you call it a "hit" on my brother-in-law, and failed, but Hank was seriously injured, and I wound up paying his medical bills which amounted to a little over $177,000. Upon recovery, Hank was bent on revenge, working with a man named Hector Salamanca, he plotted to kill Fring, and did so. In fact, the bomb that he used was built by me, and he gave me no option in it. I have often contemplated suicide, but I'm a coward. I wanted to go to the police, but I was frightened. Hank had risen in the ranks to become the head of the Albuquerque DEA, and about that time, to keep me in line, he took my children from me. For 3 months he kept them. My wife, who up until that point, had no idea of my criminal activities, was horrified to learn what I had done, why Hank had taken our children. We were scared. I was in Hell, I hated myself for what I had brought upon my family. Recently, I tried once again to quit, to end this nightmare, and in response, he gave me this. I can't take this anymore. I live in fear every day that Hank will kill me, or worse, hurt my family. I... All I could think to do was to make this video in hope that the world will finally see this man, for what he really is.
